Text.Value: There was a crack of thunder and a gust of wind. A storm descended -
That's when I felt Mizora's lips against my ear, and heard that same canny whisper.
I could never be so disloyal to Baldur's Gate.
*As the maelstrom howls, Mizora's lips press to your ear. 'She will destroy Baldur's Gate. Grant me your soul - and I will give you the power to save it', she whispers.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Wyll ends the mind meld at the end of the line.

Text.Value: You were right, of course - the new eye is a sending stone, courtesy of Mizora. She uses it to track my location and call from a distance.

EditorData.logicalname: Accused Wyll of sending stone eye before

Text.Value: Around each totem, five robed figures were chanting. First softly, then loud as a banshee's wail.
She read the terms while two devils stood witness. And I said yes. One soul for one city.
If you remember, I'd heard a whisper in the night directing me to Dusthawk Hill. That's where I found the cultists, joined in ritual prayer.
I'll paint the clearest picture I can.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Wyll removes his hand from his head, No mind meld occurs.

Text.Value: That's when the Cult of the Dragon made its move.
My clan is my home. I would give up life and limb to see them safe.
We'll find you a way out of this pact, I'm sure of it.
Godsdamnit, I'll never be rid of her. The more I want to shake her leash, the tighter she pulls it.
These infernal talents are useful, I admit. Once they're gone, I'll have to rely my wits and my training. They'll have to do.
So Zariel's asset was none other than Mizora herself. Of course. Tricks on top of tricks on top of tricks.
A brave choice. And a frightening one.
I'd give my life if it meant keeping the residents safe.
I tried to tell him the truth, but my mouth couldn't form the words. I led him to the battlefield, but Mizora had swept it clean.
Yes - my father is a Grand Duke of Baldur's Gate, and I am his only son.

EditorData.logicalname: Didn't say his father was a Grand Duke

Text.Value: But I've got only six months before I'm made a free man, thanks be to the Triad.
The place could burn to cinder for all I care.
No, scratch that. Thanks be to you.
*The Cult of the Dragon - a fractured religion. Some believers hold that undead dragons will inherit the world.*
She came on orders of her mistress Zariel.
*The Cult of the Dragon - a fractured religion. Some believers hold that undead dragons will inherit the world.*
I understand.
I could flee to the Spine of the World or the depths of the Lowerdark, and still never shake her.
Another time, then. I'll hold nothing back.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Wyll removes his hand from his head.

Text.Value: Once you're stuck to a devil, they're hard to brush off. But you - you make me think I still have a chance.
Is being pacted all that bad? There'd be no Blade of Frontiers without your warlock talents.
The cultists choked on our poisons and burned from our flames. When we were done, all that remained were five greyed orbs atop a pile of ash.
*Your head tingles. Wyll wants to show you what happened.*
Let's finish this tale later, all right?
My soul was bound and my lips were sealed.
Use your words, Wyll, and leave my mind alone.

EditorData.stateContext: Wyll holds his head, waiting for player to mind meld.

Text.Value: If Crèche K'liir were in danger, I'd rage until every last assailant was dead.
I had Mizora at my side - and the archdevil Zariel guided our hands that day.
I have my father's training, I have cunning, I have my wits. If I ever manage to break this pact, they'll more than do.
It is. And I did.
But I'd only tell you that if you were wrong. This is the hand I was dealt. I need to make the most of it.
The Cult of the Dragon had infiltrated Baldur's Gate? To what end?
'She will destroy Baldur's Gate. Grant me your soul - and I will give you the power to save it.'

EditorData.stateContext: Wyll and player are in mind meld.

Text.Value: As would I - and more.
*Others worship the dragon goddess Tiamat and intend to summon her to Faerûn.*
Surely Mizora doesn't care about Baldur's Gate. Why would she want to save it?
Then you know loyalty. And you know I did what had to be done.
*Your tadpole shivers as your mind bonds with Wyll's. Your memories of freeing Mizora are now his, too.*
Zariel's asset was none other than Mizora herself. Of course. Tricks on top of tricks on top of tricks.
A religion devoted to conjuring the most evil of goddesses, the dragon Tiamat.
'Unhappy' doesn't begin to describe it.
It is. The one scar I ever bore of it.
There they were, gathered at the foot of the Hill.
We're fortunate you can keep your powers until then. We're going to need them.
Sacrificing your soul to save the city was a brave thing to do.
Give it up, Wyll. She owns your soul, so you better get used to it.
You took on twenty-five cultists on your own? I find that hard to believe.
Yes. But first, a question. If your home were under siege, what would you sacrifice to save it?
*Others worship your goddess, the dragon Tiamat, and intend to summon her to Faerûn.*
I have my father's training, I have cunning, I have my wits. And they'll have to do.
I don't know that it was brave. I just know that it was right.
Tiamat made a play for power. Zariel had other plans. That's the most Mizora's ever said - all that mattered was that she got her prize:
First, we kill Ketheric Thorm. Then, I'll tell you everything you want to know.
First, we kill Ketheric Thorm. Then I'll tell you everything you want to know.
She didn't - she came on order of her mistress Zariel.
Orbs of dragonkind. Could it be? I thought only three were left.
Below the mount I saw five totems with dragon heads carved on top. Each head held a massive orb in its jaws.
The Grand Duke left a mere boy in charge? That can't have gone well.
It was brave, what you did for the city.

EditorData.logicalname: Already went down cult battle path

EditorData.stateContext: Wyll and player not in mind meld

Text.Value: The Coast needs the Blade, and I have no intention of turning my back on it.
*Atop each totem, a dragon's head is carved, and a massive orb held in its mouth. The cultists chant, first softly, then crying to the starless sky.*
Mizora said you can talk about your pact and exile. It's time I know the whole truth.
He returned to an unsuspecting city and a wayward son with a smirking devil at his side.
I wouldn't give up my soul, if that's what you're getting at.
*There is a crack of thunder, a gust of wind - and a dragon's white head appears in the storm, the first of Tiamat's five heads.*
After, he said only one word: 'Go.' So I did.
The Blade of Frontiers is fuelled by more than Avernus' flames.
I grabbed a rapier and set out. There wasn't a cloud in the sky, yet not a single star was shining.
What's the Cult of the Dragon? I've never heard of them.
Nod and let Wyll continue his story.
And what about your father the Grand Duke?
I can't imagine how. The pact binds her as tightly as it binds me.
I burned with the fires of Avernus and oozed the rot of Dis.
It's not too late to change your mind. There'd be no Blade without your warlock talents.
Another pet added to her warlock menagerie.
The moment I agreed, I burned with the fires of Avernus and oozed the rot of Dis.
Fiercely loyal to your people. Then you'll understand that I did what had to be done.
Allow Wyll to share his memory with you.
She never stops, does she. Not for a second.
I should be telling you to find your mettle. Have a little faith, push against the raging winds. That sort of thing.
Is that how you lost your eye - in the battle with the Cult of the Dragon?
*There is a crack of thunder, a gust of wind - and a dragon's white head appears in the storm.*
All I have to do is stay alive. That should be easy enough, with someone of your skill at my side.
A tenday after father left, I heard a whisper as I slept. 'Dusthawk Hill. The Queen of Chaos awakens. Go alone.'
Not just a boy - a Ravengard, schooled in the four pillars: Courage, insight, strategy, justice.
You're positively brimming with confidence. Mind if I borrow a handful?
*In the looming shadow of the mount, five groups of five figures each encircle a lofty totem.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Wyll holds hand to head. Wyl land player mind meld. It is absolutely fine to just show the characters during the story.

Text.Value: What was it father said? 'Fear is what you feel, courage is what you do.'
We'll return to this subject later.
- and one of Tiamat's five heads appeared from within it.
I showed him my stone eye - but he only turned away.
Six months is a long time. Time enough to weasel her way out of her promise.
Leave.
I was seventeen. Father - Ulder Ravengard - had just been named a Grand Duke, and was called away to Elturel to help settle a dispute.
Mizora replaced it with a sending stone. She uses it to track my location and speak from a distance.
To conjure the Dragon Queen and lay waste to Baldur's Gate.

Synopsis: Default dialogue when speaking to Wyll during exploration.
